#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:1
msgid "Cluster Programming"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:3
msgid ""
"A **thread block cluster** is a group of thread blocks guaranteed to run "
"simultaneously on SMs within the same GPC (Graphics Processing Cluster). "
"Introduced in Hopper (SM 90), clusters give you something that standard CUDA "
"does not: **cross-block shared memory access** without going through global "
"memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:9
msgid ""
"In normal CUDA, thread blocks are independent. Block 0 cannot read block 1's "
"shared memory. With clusters, the hardware maps all cluster members' shared "
"memory into a unified **distributed shared memory (DSMEM)** address space. "
"Any thread in the cluster can read any block's shared memory — directly, at "
"shared memory latency, no global memory round-trip."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:15
msgid ""
"cuda-oxide exposes clusters through `cuda_device::cluster` and the "
"`#[cluster_launch]` attribute. This chapter covers the programming model, "
"DSMEM access patterns, and how clusters combine with TMA multicast for high-"
"performance matrix kernels."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:21
msgid ""
"[CUDA Programming Guide — Thread Block Clusters](https://docs.nvidia.com/"
"cuda/cuda-programming-guide/#thread-block-clusters) for the hardware "
"specification, GPC constraints, and maximum cluster sizes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:27
msgid "The cluster model"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:33
msgid ""
"A 4-block cluster. Each block has its own shared memory, but the hardware "
"maps all four into a unified DSMEM space. Blocks can read each other's "
"shared memory after a `cluster_sync()` barrier. The dashed arrows show cross-"
"block DSMEM reads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:39
msgid ""
"A cluster is defined at launch time. The hardware schedules all blocks in a "
"cluster onto SMs within the same GPC, ensuring low-latency cross-block "
"communication. The maximum cluster size is architecture-dependent — Hopper "
"supports up to 8 blocks per cluster."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:44
msgid "Declaring a cluster kernel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:46
msgid "In cuda-oxide, you annotate the kernel with `#[cluster_launch]`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../advanced/cluster-programming.md:48
msgid ""
"use cuda_device::{kernel, cluster_launch, thread, cluster, SharedArray};\n"
"\n"
"#[kernel]\n"
"#[cluster_launch(4, 1, 1)]\n"
"pub fn cluster_kernel(/* ... */) {\n"
"    // This kernel runs with clusters of 4 blocks in the X dimension\n"
"    let rank = cluster::block_rank();\n"
"    let size = cluster::cluster_size();\n"
"    // ...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

